      <hedline>
        <hl1>Old, Frail and on Costly Drugs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Pankaj Gupta letter, commenting on July 12 article on prescription drug program for elderly pending in Senate, says doctors can do their part to help bring down escalating out-of-pocket costs for medication by discussing affordability, suggesting generic drugs or even pursuing alternative forms of medicine</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Senate Chairman Offers Proposal on Drug Benefits'' (front page, July 12):</p>
        <p>As the political debate continues on how to provide a prescription drug benefit for the elderly, more doctors are writing more prescriptions for more expensive drugs that sometimes are not even taken by our frail patients.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Senate Chairman Offers Proposal on Drug Benefits'' (front page, July 12):</p>
        <p>As the political debate continues on how to provide a prescription drug benefit for the elderly, more doctors are writing more prescriptions for more expensive drugs that sometimes are not even taken by our frail patients.</p>
        <p>In the meantime, we as doctors can do our share in helping bring the escalating out-of-pocket cost for prescription drugs down for our elderly patients. We can start by discussing affordability, suggest generic drugs or even pursue alternative forms of medicine. This will promote patient compliance, strengthen the doctor-patient relationship and help ease the financial burden of health expenditures that our graying Americans bear.</p>
        <p>PANKAJ GUPTA, M.D.  Framingham, Mass., July 12, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a geriatrician.</p>
      </block>
